Information dimension can be defined as follows: 
d_I = n - \lim_{D \to 0} \frac{\lim_{t \to \infty} h[\rho_t^D]}{\log\frac{1}{\sqrt D}}
where \rho_t^D is the finite time solution to the FPE. Is it possible to flip the order of the limits with a smart substitution or something like that? I know that \rho_t^0 is smooth

Yes.  All we have done is pick a **one–dimensional path**  
\[
\bigl(D,\,t\bigr)\;=\;\bigl(D,\,t(D)\bigr),\qquad  
t(D)=\alpha\,D^{-1}\log\tfrac1D,\;\;\alpha>1/c,
\tag{1}
\]
inside the half-plane \(\{D>0,\;t>0\}\).  
Because \(t(D)\) is strictly decreasing for small \(D\), it is invertible; call the inverse \(D(t)\).  Writing the very same curve as  
\[
\bigl(D,\,t\bigr)\;=\;\bigl(D(t),\,t\bigr),
\tag{2}
\]
changes only the *parameterisation*, not the points you visit.  Hence

\[
d_I
= n-\lim_{D\downarrow0}
     \frac{h\!\bigl[\rho^{\,D}_{\,t(D)}\bigr]}
          {\tfrac12\log\!\dfrac1D}
   \;=\;
  n-\lim_{t\to\infty}
     \frac{h\!\bigl[\rho^{\,D(t)}_{\,t}\bigr]}
          {\tfrac12\log\!\dfrac1{D(t)}} .
\]

Both limits evaluate exactly the same sequence of densities; the choice “\(t\) as a function of \(D\)” versus “\(D\) as a function of \(t\)” is purely notational.  Crucially, **for every point on the path the Fokker–Planck evolution has been run with a constant diffusion coefficient** (the \(D\) appropriate to that point).  Nothing inside the PDE is time-dependent—only the way we **sample** solutions varies.
